{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcwLxXVxnkN43ey76ygSN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Bash for-loops come in a few forms:\n\n**List / word iteration**\n```bash\nfor i in 1 2 3; do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Range with brace expansion**\n```bash\nfor i in {1..5}; do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n# with a step: {0..10..2} -> 0 2 4 6 8 10\n```\n\n**C-style**\n```bash\nfor ((i = 0; i < 5; i++)); do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over command output / globs**\n```bash\nfor f in *.txt; do\n  echo \"$f\"\ndone\n\nfor user in $(cat users.txt); do\n  echo \"$user\"\ndone\n```\n\nA few tips:\n- Always quote `\"$var\"` to avoid word-splitting surprises.\n- To loop over array elements: `for x in \"${arr[@]}\"; do ... done`.\n- One-liner: `for i in 1 2 3; do echo \"$i\"; done` (note the semicolons before `do` and `done`)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5741,"cache_read_input_tokens":16984,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5741},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2084f545-0c04-4202-8c07-01e73badb74c","uuid":"186ee52b-c787-476a-aec7-027589fccc96","request_id":"req_011CcwLxWWRzhoXXky4uQSd7"}
